2) Evaluation of the two candidate CDs against those points:
- CD 1 features warm tape sheen, preserved microdynamics and low compression (good), midrange tactile/breathy vocals up front (good), and dynamics‑preserving mastering (good). However it emphasizes "lush multitracked harmonies" and "wide, airy stereo imaging" and "palpable melodic solos." Those attributes suggest a more produced, multi‑layered vocal approach and more prominent instrumental solos and a wider soundstage — all of which work against my priority for intimate, front‑and‑center duet interplay and spare arrangements. The multitracking and wide imaging risk diluting the close, people‑in‑a‑room duet sound I favor, and the presence of prominent solos risks the indulgent instrumental space I prefer to avoid.
